<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-003-376 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 572 828</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Dec 2 1991 v8 n36 p75(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Striking the right balance for token ring and Ethernet. (includesrelated articles on difficulties with integration, problems withbridges)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Smalley, Eric.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>More and more users are using VAXes as servers for a variety ofmachines in heterogeneous environments.andP;  The Ethernet architecturehas long dominated VAX networking, but microcomputer LANs areappearing at many VAX sites and Ethernet does not enjoy dominancein the microcomputer arena.andP;  Thirty-eight percent of currentmicrocomputer LANs use IBm's Token-Ring topology, and Token-Ringaccounts for 59 percent of planned LANs.andP;  Token-Ring nodesincreasingly must communicate with VAX hosts via the Local Areatransport protocol.andP;  Token-Ring bridges operate differently fromEthernet bridges; Ethernet uses transparent bridging, but IBM usesa 'source routing' scheme for its Token Ring networks.andP;  Sourcerouting must exist in a separate internetwork domain.andP;  Ethernetand Token Ring have little in common because they evolved fromdifferent paradigms; Ethernet is based on carrier sense multipleaccess and collision detection, while Token-Ring is a loop onwhich a token is passed from end station to end station.andP;  Packetacknowledgement is one major problem with integrating Token-Ringand Ethernet networks.andP;  The sending station strips packets off atoken ring as they return and cannot wait for a bridge to forwardany acknowledgement from the receiving station on the other side.andO;The DECnet protocol suit uses Ethernet and has its own specialmulticast addresses.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     System SelectionNetwork ArchitectureToken Ring NetworksEthernetLocal Area NetworksUser Needs.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablegraph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>